But, again, there&#39;s: RDF; the things that we want to describe using RDF;
and the way that HTTP may be used to distinguish and relate them.

Can we respect this and fling stones only with the message: &quot;I don&#39;t
believe a document about a car is different from the car&quot;, versus &quot;I don&#39;t
like the solution in HTTP&quot;, versus &quot;RDF is weird&quot;?

Barry


On Tue, Apr 3, 2012 at 2:03 PM, Alexander Johannesen &lt;
alexander.johannesen@...&gt; wrote:

&gt;
&gt; On Apr 3, 2012 10:15 PM, &quot;Barry Norton&quot; &lt;barrynorton@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; httpRange-14, as its name suggests, is an HTTP issue not an RDF one.
&gt;
&gt; Ahem, no, that would be a bit of a red herring, I&#39;m afraid. The name stems
&gt; from dereferencing function in HTTP, and it was from the W3C issue tracker,
&gt; issue 14, where it&#39;s the other way around; it&#39;s the RDF community which has
&gt; / had issues with HTTP for *their* purposes.
&gt;
&gt; I admittedly have a foot in three camps; HTTP/REST, RDF and Topic Maps, a
&gt; kind of tripod from War of the Webs, and I think the &quot;problem&quot; that&#39;s
&gt; flaring up these days are remnants and additional context to what
&gt; httpRange-14 was about, but not the same thing;
&gt;
&gt; Identity management. And the problem is RDF&#39;s lack of a vocabulary (and
&gt; framework) that reflect that HTTP used as identifiers are ambiguous,
&gt; faulty, flaky, human and fallible. Topic Maps has a vocabulary that reflect
&gt; this, and that world don&#39;t struggle with this as much. HTTP/REST already
&gt; know they are, too, and they have no problem either.
&gt;
&gt; &gt; Linked Data, in using RDF with HTTP, encounters this issue
&gt; &gt; but does not cause it.
&gt;
&gt; They &quot;encounter this issue&quot; only by virtue of needing it to be something
&gt; it was never designed to be. HttpRange-14 was an amazingly bad &quot;solution&quot;,
&gt; and LinkedData is poking a sore not yet healed.
&gt;
&gt; IMHO, of course. :)
&gt;
&gt; Alex
&gt;

